It is useful to find a simple indicator for the nonlinear photoconductivity. Because the photocurrent is proportional to the resonant transition rate, the imaginary dielectric function or the optical conductivity may provide such an indicator. In other words, the optical conductivity is the sum of all allowed transitions equally while the photoconductivity is to sum them with the velocity weight (see Eq. (6)). As shown in Fig. 2c, the optical conductivity Ïxx is strongly correlated to Ïxxx\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
